Class TreeBoundedQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.google.common.collect.ForwardingObject

          • com.palamida.util.collect.TreeBoundedQueue<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements held in this queue
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    BoundedQueue<E>, SortedCollection<E>, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Queue<E>

    public final class TreeBoundedQueue<E>
extends ForwardingQueue<E>
implements BoundedQueue<E>, SortedCollection<E>, Serializable, Cloneable
    An implementation of BoundedQueue backed by a TreeQueue. The elements of this queue are sorted according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Inserting null elements is prohibited. Attempting to insert non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException.

    The first element (the head) of this queue is considered to be the least element with respect to the specified ordering. Elements with equal priority are ordered according to their insertion order.

    When the queue is full the offer(E) method behaves according to the following policy: if the element to be added has higher priority than the lowest priority element currently in the queue, the new element is added and the lowest priority element is removed; else the new element is rejected. The backing TreeQueue maintains references to the highest and lowest elements in the queue; rejecting an element is an O(1) operation.

    The add(E) and addAll(Collection) operations will throw an IllegalStateException when the queue is full and a new element is rejected; as required by the contract of Queue.add(E).

    Bounded priority queues are useful when implementing n-best algorithms (e.g. finding the best n elements in an arbitrary collection).

    This queue is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this queue concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    Refer to TreeQueue for details of the underlying implementation.

    Zhenya Leonov

      • from

        public static <E> TreeBoundedQueue<E> from(Collection<? extends E> elements)
        Creates a new TreeBoundedQueue containing the elements of, and having its capacity equal to the number of elements in the specified collection. If the collection is an instance of SortedSet, PriorityQueue, MinMaxPriorityQueue, or SortedCollection this queue will be ordered according to the same ordering. Otherwise, this queue will be ordered according to the natural ordering of its elements.
        Parameters:
        elements - the collection whose elements are to be placed into the queue
        Returns:
        a new TreeBoundedQueue containing the elements of the specified collection
        Throws:
        ClassCastException - if elements of the specified collection cannot be compared to one another according to the priority queue's ordering
        NullPointerException - if any of the elements of the specified collection or the collection itself is null
        IllegalArgumentException - if the specified collection is empty

        public boolean add(E e)
        Description copied from interface: java.util.Collection
        Ensures that this collection contains the specified element (optional operation). Returns true if this collection changed as a result of the call. (Returns false if this collection does not permit duplicates and already contains the specified element.)

        Collections that support this operation may place limitations on what elements may be added to this collection. In particular, some collections will refuse to add null elements, and others will impose restrictions on the type of elements that may be added. Collection classes should clearly specify in their documentation any restrictions on what elements may be added.

        If a collection refuses to add a particular element for any reason other than that it already contains the element, it must throw an exception (rather than returning false). This preserves the invariant that a collection always contains the specified element after this call returns.
